Red Wine Physicochemical Properties and Quality by Oliver Koch

Introduction to the Dataset

The dataset is related to red variants of the Portuguese Vinho Verde wine. It contains physical and chemical properties from objective measurements and a sensory assessment of the quality of the wine (median of at least 3 evaluations made by wine experts).

The dataset is available at this URL: https://s3.amazonaws.com/udacity-hosted-downloads/ud651/wineQualityReds.csv

The details are described in P. Cortez, A. Cerdeira, F. Almeida, T. Matos and J. Reis. Modeling wine preferences by data mining from physicochemical properties. In Decision Support Systems, Elsevier, 47(4):547-553. ISSN: 0167-9236, available at http://www3.dsi.uminho.pt/pcortez/wine5.pdf

Attribute information:

Input variables (based on physicochemical tests):

  1. Fixed acidity (tartaric acid - g / dm^3): most acids involved with wine or fixed or nonvolatile (do not evaporate readily)
  2. Volatile acidity (acetic acid - g / dm^3): the amount of acetic acid in wine, which at too high of levels can lead to an unpleasant, vinegar taste
  3. Citric acid (g / dm^3): found in small quantities, citric acid can add freshness and flavor to wines
  4. Residual sugar (g / dm^3): the amount of sugar remaining after fermentation stops, its rare to find wines with less than 1 gram/liter and wines with greater than 45 grams/liter are considered sweet
  5. Chlorides (sodium chloride - g / dm^3): the amount of salt in the wine
  6. Free sulfur dioxide (mg / dm^3): the free form of SO2 exists in equilibrium between molecular SO2 (as a dissolved gas) and bisulfite ion; it prevents microbial growth and the oxidation of wine
  7. Total sulfur dioxide (mg / dm^3): amount of free and bound forms of S02; in low concentrations, SO2 is mostly undetectable in wine, but at free SO2 concentrations over 50 ppm, SO2 becomes evident in the nose and taste of wine
  8. Density (g / cm^3): the density of water is close to that of water depending on the percent alcohol and sugar content
  9. pH: describes how acidic or basic a wine is on a scale from 0 (very acidic) to 14 (very basic); most wines are between 3-4 on the pH scale
  10. Sulphates (potassium sulphate - g / dm3): sulphates: a wine additive which can contribute to sulfur dioxide gas (S02) levels, wich acts as an antimicrobial and antioxidant
  11. Alcohol (% by volume): the percent alcohol content of the wine

Output variable (based on sensory data):

  1. Quality. Score between 0 (very bad) and 10 (very good)

What is the structure of your dataset?

## [1] 1599   14

The dataset has 12 variables and 1599 observations. All variables except quality are real numbers. Quality is an integer variable. There are no missing values. There are no obviously incorrect values (like negative values.)

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The wine quality is the main feature of interest. As suggested in the datasets documentation, it was created the purpose of developing regression models that can predict the wine quality from physical & chemical measurement results.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

To me, the most interesting question is which variables have the strongest influence on wine quality. Potentially, all variables may have an influence.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

I created a categorical variable grade from quality.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

Alcohol and citric acid content have highly asymmetrical, almost triangular distributions.

Quality has a bell-shaped distribution, there are few good ones and even fewer bad ones.

Bivariate Plots Section

A pair plot (scatterplot matrix) provides a first overview of dependencies and potential correlations between variables:

Again a pair plot, this time using the categorical quality value:

For the main variable of interest (quality), the highest correlations are with volatile acidity, alcohol, and sulphates.

High values of correlation also occur in these groups:

  • volatile acidity, fixed.acidity, citric acid, density, pH
  • density, alcohol, pH, fixed.acidity, citric.acid, residual.sugar

Which variables influence quality?

The following plots highlight patterns between the measured variables and the wine quality:

  • alcohol, density, total.sulfur.dioxide, volatile acidity
  • free sulfur dioxide and residual sugar do not have an influence.
  • nonlinear relationships (which are not captured by linear correlation measures or linear models): citric acid, chlorides, sulphates

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?

The alcohol content has the strongest influence on wine quality. The variables with the next highest correlation coefficients are sulphates and volatile acidity.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?

Relationships exist

  • among acidity related variables (pH, citric acid, fixed acidity, volatile acidity).
  • between density and almost all other variables (because the density of the wine depends on the concentration of the ingredients). Most prominent influences from alcohol and residual sugar.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The strongest (linear) relationship is between total sulfur dioxide and free sulfur dioxide.

Multivariate Plots Section

Explore relationship between quality, alcohol, volatile acidity, sulphates

In the plots above, bad and good wines are separated - if there were just good ones and bad ones, the three variables could be used to classify wines. However, the majority of wines are in the medium group, and they cover the whole range of values, making a classification (with the given variables and linear decision boundaries) difficult.

Reflection

The dataset can be used to predict the wine quality from physical/chemical measurements.

Difficulties with this dataset:

  • the majority of data lies in the medium range; there are relatively few good or bad examples. There are no samples for extreme cases (quality below three or above 8).
  • There are nonlinear relationships between some variables (e.g.citric acid and quality). Linear correlation measures do not capture these.

Successes:

  • Alcohol content is a good indicator for wine quality
  • There are some correlations between the variables (e.g.fixed acidity and pH). These could be used to eliminate some of the variables and reduce the number of dimensions of the problem.

Enriching the analysis:

  • More data for extreme cases (good / bad wines)
  • use nonlinear models
  • use dimensionality reduction
